@end menu

@node Introduction, Tutorial, Top, Top
@chapter Introduction

guile-dbi provides a simple, generic, easy-to-use scheme/guile interface
to SQL databases, such as Postgres, MySQL or SQLite.

The system is split into two parts: the DBI (database independent)
part, which provides the scheme interfaces, and the DBD (database
dependent) plugins, which connect to the actual SQL server. Currently,
there are DBD backends for Postgres, MySQL and SQLite3.

@section History

In 2004, Maurizio Boriani wrote:
<<I was looking around for a generic database library for guile scheme
implementation and found some projects. But them, actually, wasn't
really 'dynamic', simply compiled with different backend; I was
looking for something which permit me to link database driver at
runtime (like dbi systems for perl or php, tcl and so on), but
not found it. So I write it.>>

In 2008, Linas Vepstas wrote:
<<I was looking for a generic SQL database interface for guile, and
this was the only one that was documented, and held any promise of
working. After a few bug fixes, it worked to my satisfaction, and
I now use it in one of my projects (the OpenCog NLP subsystem).>>

@section Getting Guile DBI

You can find the latest version of Guile DBI at its project page,
@url{http://github.com/opencog/guile-dbi/}.

@*
In the file download area, there are dbi and driver tarballs.

@node Tutorial, Reference, Introduction, Top
@chapter Tutorial

The Scheme interface is very simple.
There are only 6 functions: @code{dbi-open},
@code{dbi-close}, @code{dbi-query}, @code{dbi-params-query},
@code{dbi-get_status} and @code{dbi-get_row}.

@*
Guile DBI supports any database for which a DBD backend is written.
Currently, these are MySQL, Postgres and SQLite.

Here's an example usage, using SQLite3:
@example
(use-modules (dbi dbi))

;; Log into the database.
(define db-obj (dbi-open "sqlite3" "my-example-db"))

;; Create a table.
(dbi-query db-obj "create table hellotable(id int, name varchar(15))")

;; Look at the return status of the last SQL command
(display db-obj) (newline)

;; Populate the table with values.
(dbi-query db-obj "insert into hellotable ('id', 'name') values('33', 'ola')")
(dbi-query db-obj "insert into hellotable ('id', 'name') values('34', 'dzien dobre')")
(dbi-query db-obj "insert into hellotable ('id', 'name') values('44', 'annyong haseyo')")
(display db-obj) (newline)

;; Display each of the rows of the table, in turn.
(dbi-query db-obj "select * from hellotable")
(display db-obj) (newline)
(write (dbi-get_row db-obj)) (newline)
(write (dbi-get_row db-obj)) (newline)
(write (dbi-get_row db-obj)) (newline)
(write (dbi-get_row db-obj)) (newline)

;; Close the database.
(dbi-close db-obj)
(display db-obj) (newline)

@end example

The same example rewritten to use @code{dbi-params-query} with
parameterized queries.  Parameter placeholders use the driver-native
syntax: @code{?} for SQLite3 and MySQL, @code{$1 $2 @dots{}} for
PostgreSQL.

@example
(use-modules (dbi dbi))

(define db-obj (dbi-open "sqlite3" "my-example-db"))

;; Create a table (no parameters needed here).
(dbi-query db-obj "create table hellotable(id int, name varchar(15))")

;; Insert rows using parameterized queries.
;; Values are passed as extra arguments after the SQL string.
(dbi-params-query db-obj
  "insert into hellotable (id, name) values (?, ?)" '(33 "ola"))
(dbi-params-query db-obj
  "insert into hellotable (id, name) values (?, ?)" '(34 "dzien dobre"))
(dbi-params-query db-obj
  "insert into hellotable (id, name) values (?, ?)" '(44 "annyong haseyo"))

;; Query with a parameter in the WHERE clause.
(dbi-params-query db-obj
  "select * from hellotable where id > ?" '(30))
(let loop ((row (dbi-get_row db-obj)))
  (when row
    (display row) (newline)
    (loop (dbi-get_row db-obj))))

(dbi-close db-obj)
@end example

Here's another example, using the MySQL database. This example assumes
that the MySQL server is running, and that a table named "pippo" has
already been created and populated with data:

@example
#!/usr/bin/guile -e main -s
!#

(use-modules (dbi dbi))

(define ciccio (dbi-open "mysql" "user:pass:pluto:tcp:localhost:3306"))
(define ret #f)
;; (define ciccio (dbi-open "mysql" "user:pass:pluto:socket:/tmp/mysql.sock"))

(define main
  (lambda (args)
    (display "HERE")(newline)
    (display ciccio)(newline)
    (dbi-query ciccio "select * from pippo")
    (display ciccio)(newline)
    (set! ret (dbi-get_row ciccio))
    (while (not (equal? ret #f))
	   (display ret)(newline)
	   (set! ret (dbi-get_row ciccio))
	   )
    (display ret)(newline)

))
@end example

Login credentials for PostgreSQL work similarly:
@example
#!/usr/bin/guile -e main -s
!#

(use-modules (dbi dbi))

(define conxion (dbi-open "postgresql" "user:pass:pluto:tcp:localhost:5432"))
(define conxion (dbi-open "postgresql" "user:pass:pluto:socket:/var/run/postgresql"))
@end example


@node Reference, Internals and Database Drivers, Tutorial, Top
@chapter Reference

@section Functions

@deffn Primitive dbi-open backend connString

Attempt to load driver @var{backend}, and connect to database passing
@var{connString} (which is connection string) to driver connect function.

If successful, it returns a @code{db-handle} object which is to be
used to reference the newly opened database connection. This object also
contains result status.

Every DBD implementation requires its own connection string format which
should be explained in its README file.

For example, to connect to Postgres, using TCP sockets, to the
localhost, at the standard, default Postgres port 5432:
@example
(dbi-open "postgresql" "user:pass:database:tcp:localhost:5432")
@end example

@end deffn


@deffn Primitive dbi-query db-handle query

Execute a query using @var{db-handle} and store status.

Example:
@example
(dbi-query db "select * from table")
@end example
@end deffn


@deffn Primitive dbi-params-query db-handle query params

Prepare @var{query} as a parameterized SQL statement, bind each element
of @var{params} (a list) to its corresponding placeholder, then execute
the statement.  This is the recommended way to pass user-supplied
values to the database because the driver handles all quoting and
escaping, eliminating SQL-injection risk.

@var{params} must be a Scheme list even when there is only one
parameter.  Pass @code{'()} when the query has no placeholders.

@var{query} must use the placeholder syntax of the target database:
@itemize @bullet
@item @strong{SQLite3}: @code{?} (positional)
@item @strong{MySQL}: @code{?} (positional)
@item @strong{PostgreSQL}: @code{$1}, @code{$2}, @dots{} (numbered)
@end itemize

Each element of @var{params} is a Scheme value.  Supported types
and their SQL mapping:
@multitable @columnfractions 0.3 0.7
@headitem Scheme type @tab SQL binding
@item boolean (@code{#t}/@code{#f}) @tab integer 1 / 0 (SQLite3, MySQL) or boolean (PostgreSQL)
@item exact integer @tab INTEGER / BIGINT
@item inexact real @tab FLOAT / DOUBLE (MySQL, SQLite3) or text representation (PostgreSQL)
@item string @tab TEXT / VARCHAR
@item @code{'()} (null list) @tab SQL NULL
@end multitable

Use @code{dbi-get_status} immediately after to check whether the
call succeeded before attempting to fetch rows.

Note: although the underlying driver receives parameters as a C
@code{argc}/@code{argv} array, the Scheme-level API takes a single
list argument.  The guile-dbi core converts the list before calling
the driver.

Example with SQLite3 / MySQL (@code{?} placeholders):
@example
(dbi-params-query db
  "insert into users (name, age) values (?, ?)" '("alice" 30))

(dbi-params-query db
  "select * from users where age > ?" (list 18))
(let loop ((row (dbi-get_row db)))
  (when row (display row) (newline)
            (loop (dbi-get_row db))))
@end example

Example with PostgreSQL (@code{$N} placeholders):
@example
(dbi-params-query db
  "select * from users where age > $1 and active = $2" '(18 #t))
@end example

@end deffn


@deffn Primitive dbi-get_status db-handle

Return a pair whose car is the status numeric code and cdr is a
status string message. @var{db-handle} should be a valid database
handle object.

@end deffn


@deffn Primitive dbi-get_row db-handle

Called after @code{dbi-query} or @code{dbi-params-query}, returns the
next row of the result set, or @code{#f} when no more rows are available.

A row is returned as an association list: a list of @code{(field-name
. value)} pairs, one per column.  Field names are strings.  Column
values use the closest Scheme type according to the following
conventions:

@multitable @columnfractions 0.35 0.3 0.35
@headitem SQL type @tab Scheme value @tab Notes
@item INTEGER / SMALLINT / BIGINT @tab exact integer @tab
@item REAL / FLOAT / DOUBLE @tab inexact real @tab
@item BOOLEAN @tab @code{#t} / @code{#f} @tab PostgreSQL only; SQLite3 stores as integer
@item TEXT / VARCHAR / CHAR @tab string @tab
@item NUMERIC / DECIMAL @tab string @tab Preserves exact representation
@item MONEY @tab string @tab Avoids locale-dependent formatting
@item BYTEA / BLOB @tab string @tab Raw bytes as a Scheme string
@item DATE / TIME / TIMESTAMP @tab string @tab ISO 8601 format
@item UUID / JSON / JSONB @tab string @tab
@item INTEGER[] / BIGINT[] @tab list of exact integers @tab PostgreSQL array types
@item SQL NULL @tab @code{(if #f #f)} (unspecified) @tab Distinct from @code{#f}
@end multitable

@strong{NULL handling}: a SQL NULL column is returned as the Scheme
unspecified value @code{(if #f #f)}, @emph{not} as @code{#f}.  This
preserves the distinction between a NULL value and a boolean false or
a missing row.  Test for it with @code{(eq? val (if #f #f))}.

When there are no more rows, @code{dbi-get_row} returns @code{#f} and
sets the status to a success code (e.g.@: @samp{row end}).  Always
check @code{dbi-get_status} if you need to distinguish an empty result
from an error.

Example:
@example
(dbi-query db "select id, name, score from results")
(let loop ((row (dbi-get_row db)))
  (when row
    (let ((id    (assoc-ref row "id"))
          (name  (assoc-ref row "name"))
          (score (assoc-ref row "score")))
      ;; score may be SQL NULL:
      (if (eq? score (if #f #f))
          (format #t "~a ~a: no score~%" id name)
          (format #t "~a ~a: ~a~%" id name score)))
    (loop (dbi-get_row db))))
@end example
@end deffn


@deffn Primitive dbi-close db-handle

This function closes @var{db-handle} and dereferences the loaded database
driver. When driver's reference count is 0, it is freed.

Example:
@example
(dbi-close db-handle)
@end example
@end deffn


